iews","+lib/","+  hotels.ts     # Hotel search/filter/sort logic + review mutations","+  bookings.ts   # Booking creation/lookup","+  schemas/      # Zod schemas shared by forms and route handlers","+  stores/       # Zustand favorites store","+  types.ts      # Shared TypeScript interfaces","+  utils/        # Price formatting, date helpers","+tests/","+  filter-hotels.spec.ts  # Hotel search/filter/sort unit tests","+  pricing.spec.ts        # Availability/price calculation tests","+  schemas.spec.ts        # Zod schema validation tests","+.github/workflows/ci.yml  # lint + test + build on push/PR","+```"," ","-The easiest way to deploy your Next.js app is to use the [Vercel Platform](https://vercel.com/new?utm_medium=default-template&filter=next.js&utm_source=create-next-app&utm_campaign=create-next-app-readme) from the creators of Next.js.","+### Data flow"," ","-Check out our [Next.js deployment documentation](https://nextjs.org/docs/app/building-your-application/deploying) for more details.","+**Search/results:** URL search params → Server Component reads params → calls `lib/hotels.ts` filter logic → renders `HotelCard` grid. No client state for filters — everything lives in the URL so links are shareable.","+","+**Hotel details:** Server Component fetches hotel + initial reviews → passes to Client Components (`DateGuestPicker`, `ReviewSection`). Availability is fetched client-side on date/guest change via the `/api/hotels/:id/availability` endpoint.","+","+**Reviews:** Initial list rendered server-side. New reviews are posted via `fetch` from `ReviewForm` (client) and prepended to local state immediately — no full page reload.","+","+**Favorites:** Zustand store persisted to `localStorage`. Toggling from any hotel card updates store instantly (optimistic). Favorites page fetches the hotel data for each saved ID on mount.","+","+**Checkout:** Server Component validates availability → passes totals to `CheckoutForm` (client). On submit, posts to `/api/bookings` (mocked payment always succeeds) → redirects to confirmation page.","+","+### Tradeoffs and known limitations","+","+- **In-memory data resets on server restart.** New reviews and bookings are stored in module-level arrays. This is appropriate for a demo; a real app would use a database.","+- **No authentication.** Favorites are per-browser (localStorage). Bookings and reviews are guest-only. Cross-device sync is out of scope.","+- **No map view.** The PRD specified Leaflet, but it was cut due to SSR/bundle complexity and time. Hotels include `lat`/`lng` fields — adding a map is straightforward.","+- **Static hotel data.** Real availability (occupancy, room inventory) is not modeled; `computeAvailability` only validates date range and guest count.","+- **No real payment.** `POST /api/bookings` discards card details and always returns `status: \"confirmed\"`.","+- **Booking persistence.** Because bookings live in memory, navigating directly to `/checkout/confirmation/:id` after a server restart shows a not-found page. This is documented in that page's copy.","+","+## What I would do next","+","+1. **Database:** Replace in-memory arrays with a lightweight DB (SQLite via Drizzle ORM, or PlanetScale for hosted MySQL). Would immediately fix the reset-on-restart limitation.","+2. **Map view:** Add Leaflet + OpenStreetMap tiles. The `lat`/`lng` fields and data model are already in place.","+3. **Auth:** Add NextAuth.js with a magic-link/email provider. Would enable persistent favorites and booking history per user.","+4. **Real payment:** Stripe test-mode integration.","+5. **Review moderation:** Basic profanity filter + admin flagging UI.","+6. **Vercel deploy:** The project is Vercel-ready — add `NEXTAUTH_SECRET` env var and deploy.","+7. **E2E tests:** Playwright happy path (search → details → checkout → confirmation).","+8. **Toast notifications:** `sonner` for favorited/review-submitted/booking-confirmed feedback.","+","+## LLM usage","+","+Claude Code (claude-sonnet-4-6) was used throughout, running as Ralph, an autonomous development agent.","+","+**What it handled:**","+- Scaffolded the entire application: data models, Zod schemas, API route handlers, all React components, pages, and tests in one session.","+- Read the Next.js 16 docs from `node_modules/next/dist/docs/` before writing routing code (caught the `params: Promise<{}>` breaking change vs. earlier Next.js versions).","+- Wrote the PRD (`docs/PRD.md`) before implementation, used it as the spec.","+","+**Approach:**","+- Prompted with the assessment brief → had Claude produce a PRD first, then implement against it.","+- Kept components small and single-responsibility; the LLM naturally produces cleaner code when each prompt has a narrow scope.","+- Reviewed all generated code before committing; corrected a handful of subtle issues (e.g. unused imports, hidden input/react-hook-form interaction).","+","+**Guardrails:**","+- All external URLs in mock data use Unsplash (no API key, public CDN images).","+- No real payment, no real PII stored.","+- Mocked payment card fields are validated client- and server-side to demo the form flow, but stripped before any processing."]}],"originalFile":"This is a [Next.js](https://nextjs.org) project bootstrapped with [`create-next-app`](https://nextjs.org/docs/app/api-reference/cli/create-next-app).\n\n## Getting Started\n\nFirst, run the development server:\n\n```bash\nnpm run dev\n# or\nyarn dev\n# or\npnpm dev\n# or\nbun dev\n```\n\nOpen [http://localhost:3000](http://localhost:3000) with your browser to see the result.\n\nYou can start editing the page by modifying `app/page.tsx`. The page auto-updates as you edit the file.\n\nThis project uses [`next/font`](https://nextjs.org/docs/app/building-your-application/optimizing/fonts) to automatically optimize and load [Geist](https://vercel.com/font), a new font family for Vercel.\n\n## Learn More\n\nTo learn more about Next.js, take a look at the following resources:\n\n- [Next.js Documentation](https://nextjs.org/docs) - learn about Next.js features and API.\n- [Learn Next.js](https://nextjs.org/learn) - an interactive Next.js tutorial.\n\nYou can check out [the Next.js GitHub repository](https://github.com/vercel/next.js) - your feedback and contributions are welcome!\n\n## Deploy on Vercel\n\nThe easiest way to deploy your Next.js app is to use the [Vercel Platform](https://vercel.com/new?utm_medium=default-template&filter=next.js&utm_source=create-next-app&utm_campaign=create-next-app-readme) from the creators of Next.js.\n\nCheck out our [Next.js deployment documentation](https://nextjs.org/docs/app/building-your-application/deploying) for more details.\n","userModified":false}}
