{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_0192KYt1C8eNAiaAjT6Xvoyy","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Looking at the home page code - there's an issue. `HotelResults` is defined as an `async function` but it's NOT actually async - it doesn't use `await`. Actually wait - it DOES call `getHotels(query)` synchronously (not async). So `async function HotelResults` is technically correct (async functions can have synchronous bodies) but unnecessary. It doesn't cause any problems though.\n\nActually wait - let me think about this more carefully. The `HotelResults` function is used inside a `<Suspense>` boundary. \n\nFor the Suspense boundary to work with Server Components, the component needs to be async and return a Promise, which it does. Even though `getHotels` is synchronous, marking the component as `async` is the right pattern here. The Server Component will resolve on the server and stream its result.\n\nBut I'm noticing something odd - `SearchBar` and `FilterPanel` are Client Components wrapped in `<Suspense>`. That doesn't make sense because Client Components don't suspend, so why are they wrapped in Suspense?\n\nOh wait, they use `useSearchParams()` which can suspend during server rendering, so the Suspense boundaries are actually necessary to prevent them from blocking the page.\n\nThe real issue is that `HotelResults` is marked `async` but doesn't actually await anything - it's synchronous. When wrapped in `<Suspense>`, React will wait for its Promise to resolve, but since there's nothing async happening, the fallback might never even display.\n\nLooking at the search params flow: the parent page awaits `searchParams` and passes them to `HotelResults`, while `SearchBar` and `FilterPanel` use `useSearchParams()` directly on the client side. This should work fine - the initial render will show the resolved params from the parent while the client-side components handle their own updates.\n\nI'm realizing that `HotelResults` is marked as async but doesn't actually await anything, so the `<Suspense>` boundary is mainly handling the initial hydration case where child components use `useSearchParams()`. The filtering itself happens synchronously on the server. The setup looks solid overall, so I should move forward with committing this work.\n\nBefore I do that, I need to clean up the install script I created since it's no longer needed.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1543,"cache_read_input_tokens":124496,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1543},"output_tokens":27,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"1a46cfe3-edd5-47d3-88ea-9b5bc1fd0648","uuid":"b5180c9c-86fb-49f3-bfc6-29bbe17d4f49","request_id":"req_011CcdTrUM3ALeRBrGqdttqE"}
